e a Contemporary Hindu Medieval City -- tHasid and Maskil: The Hasidic Tales of an American Yiddish Journalist -- tRe-Orienting Tradition: Radhakrishnan’s Hinduism -- tRights and Values in the American Constitutional Tradition -- t(Re)Making Tradition in an International Tibetan Buddhist Movement: A Lesson from Lama Gangchen and Lama Michel -- tAfterward: Tradition’s Legacy -- tList of Participants -- tIndex of Names -- tIndex of Topics0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDiese Aufsatzsammlung analysiert ‚Tradition' als Kategorie der historischen und vergleichenden Religionswissenschaft. Ausgehend von der Prämisse, viele Traditionen seien, zumindest teilweise, gesellschaftliche Erfindungen, die oftmals ideologischen Sonderinteressen dienen, wird eine große Vielfalt von Religionen und historischer Epochen behandelt.  aThis collection of essays analyzes ‛tradition’ as a category in the historical and comparative study of religion. The book questions the common assumption that tradition is simply the “passing down” or imitation of prior practices and discourses. It begins from the premise that many traditions are, at least in part, social fabrications, often deliberately serving particular ideological ends. Individual chapters examine a wide variety of historical periods and religions (Congolese, Buddhist, Christian, Confucian, Cree, Esoteric, Hawaiian, Hindu, Islamic, Jewish, New Religious Movement, and Shinto). Different sections of the book consider tradition's relation to three sets of issues: legitimation and authority; agency and identity; modernity and the West.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aAuthorityxReligious aspects. 0aReligious invention. 0aTradition (Theology). 4aReligionswissenschaft. 4aTradit